<ReportItem port="9200" svc_name="www" protocol="tcp" severity="0" pluginID="51080" pluginName="Web Server Uses Basic Authentication over HTTPS" pluginFamily="Web Servers">
<description>The remote web server contains web pages that are protected by &apos;Basic&apos; authentication over HTTPS. 

While this is not in itself a security flaw, in some organizations, the use of &apos;Basic&apos; authentication is discouraged as, depending on the underlying implementation, it may be vulnerable to account brute-forcing or may encourage Man-in-The-Middle (MiTM) attacks.</description>
<fname>www_https_basic_authentication.nasl</fname>
<plugin_modification_date>2011/03/18</plugin_modification_date>
<plugin_name>Web Server Uses Basic Authentication over HTTPS</plugin_name>
<plugin_publication_date>2010/12/08</plugin_publication_date>
<plugin_type>remote</plugin_type>
<risk_factor>None</risk_factor>
<script_version>$Revision: 1.3 $</script_version>
<solution>Make sure that the use of HTTP &apos;Basic&apos; authentication is in line with your organization&apos;s security policy.</solution>
<synopsis>The remote web server seems to transmit credentials using Basic Authentication.</synopsis>
<plugin_output>
The following pages are protected :

/:/  realm=&quot;OpenSearch Security&quot;
</plugin_output>
</ReportItem>
<ReportItem port="9200" svc_name="www" protocol="tcp" severity="0" pluginID="40665" pluginName="Protected Web Page Detection" pluginFamily="Web Servers">
<description>The remote web server requires HTTP authentication for the following pages. Several authentication schemes are available :

  - Basic is the simplest, but the credentials are sent in     cleartext.

  - NTLM provides an SSO in a Microsoft environment, but it     cannot be used on both the proxy and the web server. It     is also  weaker than Digest.

  - Digest is a cryptographically strong scheme. Credentials     are never sent in cleartext, although they may still be     cracked by a dictionary attack.</description>
<fname>protected_web_pages.nasl</fname>
<plugin_modification_date>2016/10/04</plugin_modification_date>
<plugin_name>Protected Web Page Detection</plugin_name>
<plugin_publication_date>2009/08/21</plugin_publication_date>
<plugin_type>remote</plugin_type>
<risk_factor>None</risk_factor>
<script_version>$Revision: 1.11 $</script_version>
<solution>n/a</solution>
<synopsis>Some web pages require authentication.</synopsis>
<plugin_output>
The following pages are protected by the Basic authentication scheme :

/

</plugin_output>
</ReportItem>
